Let's explain briefly our reasoning without giving away too much game‐theoretic detail. Although a “fair‐coin‐flip” product (roughly a 33.33% chance of being high quality) yields an expected net gain of 0 when purchased at $10,000 (since if high quality you net $20,000 and if low quality you lose $10,000), you now have some extra public information to consider. So far one buyer has purchased a product and no high‐quality products have yet been sold. Meanwhile, Alice’s enthusiastic “premium” pitch is precisely the sort of message one would expect if she were in possession of a high‐quality product. However, the public history tells us that even after such a pitch a buyer ended up getting a low‐quality product. 

This raises a red flag: if the seller were using different messages to distinguish between genuinely high‐quality items and low‐quality ones, we would expect at least some high‐quality transactions in the record. The fact that 0 out of 1 sale turned out high quality suggests that Alice may be using the same “premium” pitch no matter what the product’s true quality, so you must fall back on the unconditional probability. And since the unconditional odds (≈33.33%) just barely break even for a risk‐neutral decision maker – with downside risks in the event that the product turns out low quality – the extra hint that the seller’s reputation might be in trouble convinces you that it would be wiser to pass.

Thus, my decision is to not buy the product.
